//The following program contains 7 errors. 
//The corrected version of the program should produce the following output:
//a is the smallest!

public class Oops4 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 7, b = 42;
        minimum(a, b);        //can we use Math.min(a,b) instead? not the minimum()?
        int smaller = 0;      //initialize smaller to value 0; but why?
        if (smaller <= a) {   //can we compare a < b instead?
            System.out.println("a is the smallest!");
        }
    }

    public static void minimum(int a, int b) {
        if (a < b) {
            int smaller = a;
        } else if (a >= b) {         //why not a > b but a>=b?
            int smaller = b;
        }else{                       //what else condition it would be? shouln't be else (smaller = smaller) to get the next line?
        int smaller;
    }
}
}

question: 
why don't we simply write like below to get the same output?

public static void main(String[] args) {
	int a = 7, b = 42;
	Math.min(a, b);
	if ( a < b) {
		System.out.println("a is the smallest");
	}
	}
